<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
There are two slides of this species in the Berlese Collection in Florence, only one of them (169/3) is labelled 
<normalizedToken originalValue="âtipicoâ">&quot;tipico&quot;</normalizedToken>
. Unfortunately, the holotype specimen is wholly unsuitable for study, and practically the same can be stated for the female mounted onto the second slide (190/19), reported from Florence. 
<bibRefCitation pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Bregetova (1977)</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1903" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1903" class="Arachnida" family="Ameroseiidae" genus="Ameroseius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ameroseius sculptilis" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sculptilis">Ameroseius sculptilis</taxonomicName>
to be identical to 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1903" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1903" class="Arachnida" family="Ameroseiidae" genus="Ameroseius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ameroseius pulcher" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulcher">Ameroseius pulcher</taxonomicName>
Westerboer, 1963, and her interpretation is accepted in this paper. I examined one quite well preserved female on a slide in the Hirschmann/Willmann Collection in Munich labelled &quot; 
<taxonomicName authority="Berlese, 1903" authorityName="Berlese" authorityYear="1903" class="Arachnida" family="Ameroseiidae" genus="Ameroseius" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ameroseius pulcher" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pulcher">Ameroseius pulcher</taxonomicName>
n. sp.&quot;. Unfortunately, this available specimen (slide) bears no type designation and specific collection data, but without doubt it belongs to the original series of Westerboer (see remarks under 
<taxonomicName authority="Bregetova, 1977" authorityName="Bregetova" authorityYear="1977" class="Arachnida" family="Ameroseiidae" genus="Ameroseiella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ameroseiella macrochelae" order="Mesostigmata" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="macrochelae">Ameroseiella macrochelae</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
